# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: field-oriented-control
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] In electrical engineering, the **alpha-beta** ( $\alpha \beta \gamma$ ) **transformation** (also known as the **Clarke transformation**) is a mathematical transformation employed to simplify the analysis of three-phase circuits.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] Conceptually it is similar to the dq0 transformation.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] One very useful application of the $\alpha \beta \gamma$ transformation is the generation of the reference signal used for space vector modulation control of three-phase inverters.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] In 1937 and 1938, Edith Clarke published papers with modified methods of calculations on unbalanced three-phase problems, that turned out to be particularly useful.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] where $i_{abc}(t)$ is a generic three-phase current sequence and $i_{\alpha \beta \gamma }(t)$ is the corresponding current sequence given by the transformation T .
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] The above Clarke's transformation preserves the amplitude of the electrical variables which it is applied to.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] where I is the RMS of $i_{a}(t)$ , $i_{b}(t)$ , $i_{c}(t)$ and $\theta (t)$ is the generic time-varying angle that can also be set to $\omega t$ without loss of generality.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] where the last equation holds since we have considered balanced currents.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] As it is shown in the above, the amplitudes of the currents in the $\alpha \beta \gamma$ reference frame are the same of that in the natural reference frame.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] The active and reactive powers computed in the Clarke's domain with the transformation shown above are not the same of those computed in the standard reference frame.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] where U is a (real) unitary matrix and the inverse coincides with its transpose.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] which is the corresponding inverse transformation.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] The $\alpha \beta \gamma$ transformation can be thought of as the projection of the three phase quantities (voltages or currents) onto two stationary axes, the alpha axis and the beta axis.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] However, no information is lost if the system is balanced, as the equation $I_{a}+I_{b}+I_{c}=0$ is equivalent to the equation for $I_{\gamma }$ in the transform.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] If the system is not balanced, then the $I_{\gamma }$ term will contain the error component of the projection.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] Thus, a $I_{\gamma }$ of zero indicates that the system is balanced (and thus exists entirely in the alpha-beta coordinate space), and can be ignored for two coordinate calculations that operate under this assumption that the system is balanced.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] This is the elegance of the Clarke transform as it reduces a three component system into a two component system thanks to this assumption.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] Another way to understand this is that the equation $I_{a}+I_{b}+I_{c}=0$ defines a plane in a euclidean three coordinate space.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] The alpha-beta coordinate space can be understood as the two coordinate space defined by this plane, i.e. the alpha-beta axes lie on the plane defined by $I_{a}+I_{b}+I_{c}=0$ .
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] This also means that in order the use the Clarke transform, one must ensure the system is balanced, otherwise subsequent two coordinate calculations will be erroneous.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] This is a practical consideration in applications where the three phase quantities are measured and can possibly have measurement error.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] The $dq0$ transform is conceptually similar to the $\alpha \beta \gamma$ transform.
[src:field-oriented-control/clarke-transformation] Whereas the $\alpha \beta \gamma$ transform is the projection of the phase quantities onto a stationary two-axis reference frame, the $dq0$ transform can be thought of as the projection of the phase quantities onto a rotating two-axis reference frame.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The **direct-quadrature-zero** (**DQZ**, **DQ0** or **DQO**, sometimes lowercase) or **Park** **transformation** (named after Robert H.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Park) is a tensor that rotates the reference frame of a three-element vector or a three-by-three element matrix in an effort to simplify analysis.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The transformation combines a Clarke transformation with a new rotating reference frame.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The Park transformation is often used in the context of electrical engineering with three-phase circuits.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The transformation can be used to rotate the reference frames of AC waveforms such that they become DC signals.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Simplified calculations can then be carried out on these DC quantities before performing the inverse transformation to recover the actual three-phase AC results.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] As an example, the Park transformation is often used in order to simplify the analysis of three-phase synchronous machines or to simplify calculations for the control of three-phase inverters.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The Park transformation is equivalent to the product of the rotation and Clarke transformation matrices.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The Clarke transformation (named after Edith Clarke) converts vectors in the *ABC* reference frame to the XYZ (also called *αβγ*) reference frame.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The primary value of the Clarke transformation is isolating that part of the *ABC*-referenced vector, which is common to all three components of the vector; it isolates the common-mode component (i.e., the *Z* component).
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The rotation converts vectors in the *XYZ* reference frame to the *DQZ* reference frame.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The rotation's primary value is to rotate a vector's reference frame at an arbitrary frequency.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The rotation shifts the signal's frequency spectrum such that the arbitrary frequency now appears as "dc," and the old dc appears as the negative of the arbitrary frequency.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] where *θ* is the instantaneous angle of an arbitrary *ω* frequency.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] To understand this transformation better, a derivation of the transformation is included.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] A rotation matrix is based on the concept of the dot product and projections of vectors onto other vectors.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] First, let us imagine two unit vectors, ${\hat {u}}_{D}$ and ${\hat {u}}_{Q}$ (the unit vectors, or axes, of the new reference frame from the perspective of the old reference frame), and a third, arbitrary, vector ${\vec {v}}_{XY}$ .
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] where ${\hat {u}}_{X}$ and ${\hat {u}}_{Y}$ are the unit basis vectors of the old coordinate system and $\theta$ is the angle between the ${\hat {u}}_{X}$ and ${\hat {u}}_{D}$ unit vectors (i.e., the angle between the two reference frames).
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] These new vector components, $v_{D}$ and $v_{Q}$ , together compose the new vector ${\vec {v}}_{DQ}$ , the original vector ${\vec {v}}_{XY}$ in terms of the new *DQ* reference frame.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Notice that the positive angle $\theta$ above caused the arbitrary vector to rotate backward when transitioned to the new *DQ* reference frame.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] In other words, its angle concerning the new reference frame is less than its angle to the old reference frame.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] This is because the reference frame, not the vector, was rotated forwards.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Actually, a forward rotation of the reference frame is identical to a negative rotation of the vector.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] If the old reference frame were rotating forwards, such as in three-phase electrical systems, then the resulting DQ vector remains stationary.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] This tensor can be expanded to three-dimensional problems, where the axis about which rotation occurs is left unaffected.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] From a linear algebra perspective, this is simply a clockwise rotation about the z-axis and is mathematically equivalent to the trigonometric difference angle formulae.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Consider a three-dimensional space with unit basis vectors *A*, *B*, and *C*.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The sphere in the figure below is used to show the scale of the reference frame for context and the box is used to provide a rotational context.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Typically, in electrical engineering (or any other context that uses three-phase systems), the three-phase components are shown in a two-dimensional perspective.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] However, given the three phases can change independently, they are by definition orthogonal to each other.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] This implies a three-dimensional perspective, as shown in the figure above.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] So, the two-dimensional perspective is really showing the projection of the three-dimensional reality onto a plane.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Three-phase problems are typically described as operating within this plane.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] To build the Clarke transformation, we actually use the Park transformation in two steps.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Our goal is to rotate the *C* axis into the corner of the box.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] This way the rotated *C* axis will be orthogonal to the plane of the two-dimensional perspective mentioned above.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The first step towards building the Clarke transformation requires rotating the *ABC* reference frame about the *A* axis.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The following figure shows how the *ABC* reference frame is rotated to the *AYC'* reference frame when any vector is pre-multiplied by the *K*1 matrix.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The *C'* and *Y* axes now point to the midpoints of the edges of the box, but the magnitude of the reference frame has not changed (i.e., the sphere did not grow or shrink).This is due to the fact that the norm of the *K*1 tensor is 1: ||*K*1|| = 1.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] This means that any vector in the *ABC* reference frame will continue to have the same magnitude when rotated into the *AYC'* reference frame.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Notice that the distance from the center of the sphere to the midpoint of the edge of the box is √2 but from the center of the sphere to the corner of the box is √3.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] That is where the 35.26° angle came from.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The angle can be calculated using the dot product.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The norm of the *K*2 matrix is also 1, so it too does not change the magnitude of any vector pre-multiplied by the *K*2 matrix.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] At this point, the *Z* axis is now orthogonal to the plane in which any *ABC* vector without a common-mode component can be found.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Any balanced *ABC* vector waveform (a vector without a common mode) will travel about this plane.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] This plane will be called the zero plane and is shown below by the hexagonal outline.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The *X* and *Y* basis vectors are on the zero plane.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Notice that the *X* axis is parallel to the projection of the *A* axis onto the zero plane.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The *X* axis is slightly larger than the projection of the *A* axis onto the zero plane.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The arbitrary vector did not change magnitude through this conversion from the *ABC* reference frame to the *XYZ* reference frame (i.e., the sphere did not change size).
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] This is true for the power-invariant form of the Clarke transformation.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The following figure shows the common two-dimensional perspective of the *ABC* and *XYZ* reference frames.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] It might seem odd that though the magnitude of the vector did not change, the magnitude of its components did (i.e., the *X* and *Y* components are longer than the *A*, *B*, and *C* components).
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Perhaps this can be intuitively understood by considering that for a vector without common mode, what took three values (*A*, *B*, and *C* components) to express, now only takes 2 (*X* and *Y* components) since the *Z* component is zero.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Therefore, the *X* and *Y* component values must be larger to compensate.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Notice that when multiplied through, the bottom row of the *KC* matrix is 1/√3, not 1/3.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] (Edith Clarke did use 1/3 for the power-variant case.) The *Z* component is not exactly the average of the *A*, *B*, and *C* components.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] If only the bottom row elements were changed to be 1/3, then the sphere would be squashed along the *Z* axis.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] This means that the *Z* component would not have the same scaling as the *X* and *Y* components.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] As things are written above, the norm of the Clarke transformation matrix is still 1, which means that it only rotates an *ABC* vector but does not scale it.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The same cannot be said for Clarke's original transformation.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] It is sometimes desirable to scale the Clarke transformation matrix so that the *X* axis is the projection of the *A* axis onto the zero plane.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] This will necessarily shrink the sphere by a factor of √2/3 as shown below.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Notice that this new *X* axis is exactly the projection of the *A* axis onto the zero plane.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] With the power-variant Clarke transformation, the magnitude of the arbitrary vector is smaller in the *XYZ* reference frame than in the *ABC* reference frame (the norm of the transformation is √2/3), but the magnitudes of the individual vector components are the same (when there is no common mode).
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] a new vector whose components are the same magnitude as the original components: 1.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] In many cases, this is an advantageous quality of the power-variant Clarke transformation.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The *X* component becomes the *D* component, which is in *direct* alignment with the vector of rotation, and the *Y* component becomes the *Q* component, which is at a *quadrature* angle to the direct component.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] In electric systems, very often the *A*, *B*, and *C* values are oscillating in such a way that the net vector is spinning.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] In a balanced system, the vector is spinning about the *Z* axis.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Very often, it is helpful to rotate the reference frame such that the majority of the changes in the *ABC* values, due to this spinning, are canceled out and any finer variations become more obvious.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] This is incredibly useful as it now transforms the system into a linear time-invariant system.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The Park transformation can be thought of in geometric terms as the projection of the three separate sinusoidal phase quantities onto two axes rotating with the same angular velocity as the sinusoidal phase quantities.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Shown above is the Park transformation as applied to the stator of a synchronous machine.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] There are three windings separated by 120 physical degrees.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The three phase currents are equal in magnitude and are separated from one another by 120 electrical degrees.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The three phase currents lag their corresponding phase voltages by $\delta$ .
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The *DQ* axes are shown rotating with angular velocity equal to $\omega$ , the same angular velocity as the phase voltages and currents.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The *D* axis makes an angle $\theta =\omega t$ with the phase *A* winding which has been chosen as the reference.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The currents $I_{D}$ and $I_{Q}$ are constant dc quantities.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] The transformation originally proposed by Robert H.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] Park differs slightly from the one given above.
[src:field-oriented-control/direct-quadrature-zero-transformation] In such transformation, the q-axis is ahead of d-axis, qd0, and the $\theta$ angle is the angle between phase-a and d-axis, as given below.
[src:field-oriented-control/space-vector-modulation] A three-phase inverter as shown to the right converts a DC supply, via a series of switches, to three output legs which could be connected to a three-phase motor.
[src:field-oriented-control/space-vector-modulation] The switches must be controlled so that at no time are both switches in the same leg turned on or else the DC supply would be shorted.
[src:field-oriented-control/space-vector-modulation] This requirement may be met by the complementary operation of the switches within a leg. i.e. if A+ is on then A− is off and vice versa.
[src:field-oriented-control/space-vector-modulation] This leads to eight possible switching vectors for the inverter, V0 through V7 with six active switching vectors and two zero vectors.
[src:field-oriented-control/space-vector-modulation] Note that looking down the columns for the active switching vectors V1-6, the output voltages vary as a pulsed sinusoid, with each leg offset by 120 degrees of phase angle.
[src:field-oriented-control/space-vector-modulation] To implement space vector modulation, a reference signal Vref is sampled with a frequency fs (Ts = 1/fs).
[src:field-oriented-control/space-vector-modulation] The reference signal may be generated from three separate phase references using the αβγ transform.
[src:field-oriented-control/space-vector-modulation] The reference vector is then synthesized using a combination of the two adjacent active switching vectors and one or both of the zero vectors.
[src:field-oriented-control/space-vector-modulation] Various strategies of selecting the order of the vectors and which zero vector(s) to use exist.
[src:field-oriented-control/space-vector-modulation] Strategy selection will affect the harmonic content and the switching losses.
[src:field-oriented-control/space-vector-modulation] More complicated SVM strategies for the unbalanced operation of four-leg three-phase inverters do exist.
[src:field-oriented-control/space-vector-modulation] In these strategies the switching vectors define a 3D shape (a hexagonal prism in $\alpha \beta \gamma$ coordinates or a dodecahedron in abc coordinates) rather than a 2D hexagon.
[src:field-oriented-control/space-vector-modulation] General SVM techniques are also available for converters with any number of legs and levels.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] FOC is used to control AC synchronous and induction motors.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] It was originally developed for high-performance motor applications that are required to operate smoothly over the full speed range, generate full torque at zero speed, and have high dynamic performance including fast acceleration and deceleration.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] However, it is becoming increasingly attractive for lower performance applications as well due to FOC's motor size, cost and power consumption reduction superiority.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] It is expected that with increasing computational power of the microprocessors it will eventually nearly universally displace single-variable scalar control (volts-per-Hertz, V/f control).
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Blaschke pioneered vector control of AC motors starting in 1968 and in the early 1970s.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Hasse in terms of proposing indirect vector control, Blaschke in terms of proposing direct vector control.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Technical University Braunschweig's Werner Leonhard further developed FOC techniques and was instrumental in opening up opportunities for AC drives to be a competitive alternative to DC drives.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Yet it was not until after the commercialization of microprocessors, that is in the early 1980s, that general purpose AC drives became available.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Barriers to use FOC for AC drive applications included higher cost and complexity and lower maintainability compared to DC drives, FOC having until then required many electronic components in terms of sensors, amplifiers and so on.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] The Park transformation has long been widely used in the analysis and study of synchronous and induction machines.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] The transformation is by far the single most important concept needed for an understanding of how FOC works, the concept having been first conceptualized in a 1929 paper authored by Robert H.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Park's paper was ranked second most important in terms of impact from among all power engineering related papers ever published in the twentieth century.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] The novelty of Park's work involves his ability to transform any related machine's linear differential equation set from one with time varying coefficients to another with time *invariant* coefficients resulting in a linear time-invariant system or LTI system.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] While the analysis of AC drive controls can be technically quite involved ("See also" section), such analysis invariably starts with modeling of the drive-motor circuit involved along the lines of accompanying signal flow graph and equations.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] In vector control, an AC induction or synchronous motor is controlled under all operating conditions like a separately excited DC motor.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Such complex stator current space vector can be defined in a (d,q) coordinate system with orthogonal components along d (direct) and q (quadrature) axes such that field flux linkage component of current is aligned along the d axis and torque component of current is aligned along the q axis.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] The induction motor's (d,q) coordinate system can be superimposed to the motor's instantaneous (a,b,c) three-phase sinusoidal system as shown in accompanying image (phases b & c not shown for clarity).
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Components of the (d,q) system current vector allow conventional control such as proportional and integral, or PI, control, as with a DC motor.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] The idea of using the park transform is to convert the system of three phase currents and voltages into a two coordinate linear time-invariant system.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] By making the system LTI is what enables the use of simple and easy to implement PI controllers, and also simplifies the control of flux and torque producing currents.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] However, it is not uncommon for sources to use combined transform three-to-two, (a,b,c)-to-(d,q) and inverse projections.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Decoupled torque and field currents can thus be derived from raw stator current inputs for control algorithm development.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Inverters can be implemented as either open-loop sensorless or closed-loop FOC, the key limitation of open-loop operation being minimum speed possible at 100% torque, namely, about 0.8 Hz compared to standstill for closed-loop operation.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] There are two vector control methods, direct or feedback vector control (DFOC) and indirect or feedforward vector control (IFOC), IFOC being more commonly used because in closed-loop mode such drives more easily operate throughout the speed range from zero speed to high-speed field-weakening.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] In DFOC, flux magnitude and angle feedback signals are directly calculated using so-called voltage or current models.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] In IFOC, flux space angle feedforward and flux magnitude signals first measure stator currents and rotor speed for then deriving flux space angle proper by summing the rotor angle corresponding to the rotor speed and the calculated reference value of slip angle corresponding to the slip frequency.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Sensorless control (see the Sensorless FOC block diagram) of AC drives is attractive for cost and reliability considerations.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Sensorless control requires derivation of rotor speed information from measured stator voltage and currents in combination with open-loop estimators or closed-loop observers.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Current is converted to ( $\alpha$ , $\beta$ ) coordinate system.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Transformed to a coordinate system rotating in rotor reference frame, rotor position is derived by integrating the speed by means of speed measurement sensor.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Rotor flux linkage vector is estimated by multiplying the stator current vector with magnetizing inductance Lm and low-pass filtering the result with the rotor no-load time constant Lr/Rr, namely, the rotor inductance to rotor resistance ratio.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Current vector is converted to (d,q) coordinate system.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] 5. d-axis component of the stator current vector is used to control the rotor flux linkage and the imaginary q-axis component is used to control the motor torque.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] While PI controllers can be used to control these currents, bang-bang type current control provides better dynamic performance.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] PI controllers provide (d,q) coordinate voltage components.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] A decoupling term is sometimes added to the controller output to improve control performance to mitigate cross coupling or big and rapid changes in speed, current and flux linkage.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] PI-controller also sometimes need low-pass filtering at the input or output to prevent the current ripple due to transistor switching from being amplified excessively and destabilizing the control.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] However, such filtering also limits the dynamic control system performance.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] High switching frequency (typically more than 10 kHz) is typically required to minimize filtering requirements for high-performance drives such as servo drives.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Voltage components are transformed from (d,q) coordinate system to ( $\alpha$ , $\beta$ ) coordinate system.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Voltage components are transformed from ( $\alpha$ , $\beta$ ) coordinate system to (a,b,c) coordinate system or fed in Pulse-Width Modulation (PWM) modulator, or both, for signaling to the power inverter section.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Although the vector control algorithm is more complicated than the Direct Torque Control (DTC), the algorithm need not be calculated as frequently as the DTC algorithm.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Also the current sensors need not be the best in the market.
[src:field-oriented-control/vector-control-motor] Thus the cost of the processor and other control hardware is lower making it suitable for applications where the ultimate performance of DTC is not required.
